{"id":"2204.00034","submitter":"Patrik Keller","authors":"Patrik Keller and Rainer B\\\"ohme","title":"Parallel Proof-of-Work with Concrete Bounds","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Authorization is challenging in distributed systems that cannot rely on the\nidentification of nodes. Proof-of-work offers an alternative gate-keeping\nmechanism, but its probabilistic nature is incompatible with conventional\nsecurity definitions. Recent related work establishes concrete bounds for the\nfailure probability of Bitcoin's sequential proof-of-work mechanism. We propose\na family of state replication protocols using parallel proof-of-work. Our\nbottom-up design from an agreement sub-protocol allows us to give concrete\nbounds for the failure probability in adversarial synchronous networks. After\nthe typical interval of 10 minutes, parallel proof-of-work offers two orders of\nmagnitude more security than sequential proof-of-work. This means that state\nupdates can be sufficiently secure to support commits after one block (i.e.,\nafter 10 minutes), removing the risk of double-spending in many applications.\nWe offer guidance on the optimal choice of parameters for a wide range of\nnetwork and attacker assumptions. Simulations show that the proposed\nconstruction is robust against violations of design assumptions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 31 Mar 2022 18:14:31 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 19 Sep 2022 16:10:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-20"}
